\section{Introduction}
Teaching methodologies have evolved significantly with the advent of digital technologies. This paper compares the methodologies used in \textbf{virtual} (online) and \textbf{conventional} (face-to-face) classroom settings. It discusses the differences and similarities, along with the advantages and disadvantages of each approach, while taking into account the unique variables inherent in both environments.

\section{Differences and Similarities}

\subsection{Similarities}
Both virtual and conventional classrooms aim to \textbf{facilitate learning} and \textbf{engage students}. They share the following core components:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Curriculum delivery}: Both settings use structured curricula to deliver content.
    \item \textbf{Assessment methods}: Both may employ quizzes, exams, and assignments to evaluate student performance.
    \item \textbf{Student interaction}: While the mode of interaction differs, both require some form of student-teacher and student-student interaction.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Differences}
The primary differences lie in the \textbf{environment}, \textbf{tools}, and \textbf{delivery methods}:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Environment:} 
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Conventional: In-person, physical space with desks, whiteboards, and physical materials.
            \item Virtual: Digital, remote, with tools like LMS (Learning Management Systems), video conferencing, and interactive platforms.
        \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Tools:} 
        \begin{itemize}
            \item Conventional: Whiteboards, projectors, books, physical lab equipment.
